18\u201319]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|37536|2018}}</ref>\n|Championship\n|19||0||1||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||24||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!309!!34!!19!!5!!11!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!2!!0!!341!!39\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career Total\n!375!!37!!32!!6!!15!!1!!14!!3!!2!!0!!438!!47\n|}\n\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n===International appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]]<ref>{{NFT player|26019|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{SFA Profile|id=142745|name=James Morrison}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n| 2008 || 3 || 0\n|-\n| 2009 || 2 || 0\n|-\n| 2010 || 5 || 0\n|-\n| 2011 || 9 || 1\n|-\n| 2012 || 6 || 1\n|-\n| 2013 || 4 || 1\n|-\n| 2014 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 2015 || 6 || 0\n|-\n| 2016 || 1 || 0\n|-\n| 2017 || 4 || 0\n|-\n!Total || 46 || 3\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Scotland's goal tally first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! # !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 25 May 2011 || [[Aviva Stadium]], [[Dublin]], Ireland || {{fb|WAL}} || '''1'''\u20131 || 3\u20131 || [[2011 Nations Cup]]\n|-\n| 2. || 12 October 2012 || [[Cardiff City Stadium]], [[Cardiff]], Wales || {{fb|WAL}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 1\u20132 || [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification&nbsp;\u2013 UEFA Group A|2014 World Cup qualifier]]\n|-\n| 3. || 14 August 2013 || [[Wembley Stadium]], [[London]], England || {{fb|ENG}} || '''1'''\u20130 || 2\u20133 || [[Exhibition match|Friendly]]\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Middlesbrough'''\n*[[FA Youth Cup]]: [[FA Youth Cup Finals#2003.E2.80.9304: Middlesbrough vs Aston Villa .283.E2.80.930.2C 1.E2.80.930.29|2003\u201304]]<ref name=\"Hugman2010/11\"/>\n*[[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] finalists: [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|2005\u201306]]\n\n'''West Bromwich Albion'''\n*[[Football League Championship]]: [[2007\u201308 Football League Championship|2007\u201308]]<ref name=\"Hugman2010/11\"/>\n*Football League Championship runners-up: [[2009\u201310 Football League Championship|2009\u201310]]<ref name=\"Hugman2010/11\"/>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] Player of the Year: [[2014\u201315 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n*[[SFWA International Player of the Year]]: 2011\u201312\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Scotland international footballers born outside Scotland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|James Morrison}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170503104917/http://www.wba.co.uk/team/player-profile/james-morrison/7 James Morrison profile] at the [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.]] website\n* [http://www.thefa.com/England/All-Teams/Players.aspx?p=315331 James Morrison profile] at the [[Football Association]] website\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{NFT player|id=26019}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards\n|bg = gold\n|fg = navy\n|list1 =\n{{West Bromwich Albion F.C. Player of the Year}}\n{{SFWA International Player of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morrison, James}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hummersknott Academy]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Darlington]]\n[[Category:Footballers from County Durham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Scotland international footballers]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. non-playing staff]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Morrison_(footballer)"}
{"title_page": "Oxford Review of Books", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{notability|periodicals|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper\n|name = Oxford Review of Books\n|type = Termly [[magazine]] during [[Oxford University]] term time\n|format = [[Broadsheet]]\n|foundation = 2017\n|owners = LM Publishing Ltd\n|website = https://www.the-orb.org\n|editor=Isabella Crispino, Alexander Haveron-Jones, Ella Johnson and Natalie Perman <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-orb.org/about|title=About|website=www.the-orb.org|language=en|accessdate=2019-04-09}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''Oxford Review of Books''''' is an independent cultural review [[broadsheet]] [[magazine]] produced by students of the [[University of Oxford]] sold commercially online, and by retailers in Oxford (such as [[Blackwell's]]) and newsagents across the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Northern Ireland]]; the magazine is often abbreviated to the '''''ORB'''''. The ''ORB'' was established in 2017 by [[University of Oxford]] students and one issue is published each term during [[University of Oxford]] term time. The ''ORB'' specialises in long-form book reviews and essays, as well as diary pieces, interviews, poetry and short fiction<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-orb.org/about|title=About|website=www.the-orb.org|language=en|accessdate=2019-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\n''Oxford Review of Books'' was founded in 2017 and its first issue was published on the 9th June. Its founding Editors were Daniel Kodsi, Katie Mennis and Benn Sheridan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/theorb/docs/orb_issue_1_final_cmyk|title=Oxford Review of Books Volume 1 Issue 1|website=www.issuu.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>. The ''ORB'' was modelled on the [[Times Literary Supplement]] and [[London Review of Books]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lux-mag.com/orb/|title=The Oxford Review of Books: a new student culture|website=www.lux-mag.org|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\n\n''Oxford Review of Books'' is published with the permission of Luxury Magazines Publishing Ltd, responsible for LUX Magazine, a luxury lifestyle magazine published by Darius Sanai, an Editor-in-Chief at Cond\u00e9 Nast, and an Oxford graduate himself<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lux-mag.com/the-team/|title=The Team|website=www.lux-mag.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>, who offers guidance and support for the ''ORB''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ebe889af-4770-4ddf-9c2a-7f097328c1d9.filesusr.com/ugd/f45b4b_64f686d1c17a492b9f283f516c4b3e09.pdf|title=Publishing and Editorial Articles of Incorporation June 2019|website=www.filesusr.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>. ''Oxford Review of Books'' staff are all current [[University of Oxford]] undergraduate or postgraduate students who run the magazine while studying for their degrees. \n\nThe ''ORB'' is organised termly by a team of three to four Editors-in-Chief overseeing the production of the issue. One or two of these Editors continue on during the following term as rolling Editor(s) to ensure continuity. Editors of the publication must be current students of the [[University of Oxford]]. Although the publication is published by Darius Sanai, it enjoys editorial independence, and the ''ORB'' team are responsible for its editorial, publishing, advertising and event operations, with full responsibility for the contents and design of the publication as well as its print and distribution, events and marketing. Current Editors are advised and supported by ''The ORB'' Advisory Board (the Board), an assembly of founders and former Editors of the ''ORB'' who provide advice and guidance to the publication<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ebe889af-4770-4ddf-9c2a-7f097328c1d9.filesusr.com/ugd/f45b4b_64f686d1c17a492b9f283f516c4b3e09.pdf|title=Publishing and Editorial Articles of Incorporation June 2019|website=www.filesusr.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.\n\nThe ''ORB'' Editors oversee the management of the publication's staff, who are recruited termly through a 'Call for Staff' conducted via the ''ORB'' social media platforms. A team of Commissioning Editors are appointed to work closely with the writers throughout the editorial process and develop articles for publication. Members for the Poetry and Fiction team are hired to respectively organise the ''ORB'' termly poetry night, and to oversee submissions and appoint a judge for the ''ORB'' termly short fiction competition. A Business Director works alongside a business team to manage the publication's business and advertising interests, and a social media and marketing team are responsible for the magazine's publicity. An Artistic Director is also appointed to organise a team of artists and illustrators who produce custom artwork for each piece in publication and online<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/860756181014095/|title=ORB Call for Staff TT20|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.  \n\nThe ''ORB'' releases calls for pitches termly via their social media platforms, and it is recommended that pitches such as books reviews are between 2,500-3,000 words, and essays between 2,000 to 2,500 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/909158342861806/|title=Pitch to the ORB TT20|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.  \n\n==Format and style==\n\nThe ''ORB'' is unique amongst student publications in [[Oxford]] for its emphasis on long-form writing and [[journalism]]; each issue is composed of 32 pages and its reviews, interviews and journalistic articles are interspersed with poetry and creative fiction, and regularly features a comical section of satirical or amusing of classified adverts at the back. The ''ORB'' artistic team are commissioned to produce artwork and illustrations for publication alongside print pieces<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordunimediasoc.com/orb-a-spotlight|title=Spotlight: The Oxford Review of Books (ORB)|website=www.oxfordunimediasoc.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>. \n\n==Notable contributors==\nThe ''ORB'' is also unusual for a student publication in its printing of original works by notable poets and writers. It has published original poetry by [[Simon Armitage]], [[Lawrence Sail]] and [[Bernard O'Donoghue]]. The ''ORB'' has also interviewed notable academics and politicians, including [[Philippe Sands]], [[Anne Sebba]], [[Mary Beard]], [[Colm T\u00f3ib\u00edn]], [[Peter Singer]], [[Kwame Anthony Appiah]], [[Helen Dunmore]], [[Amia Srinivasan]], [[Quassim Cassam]], [[Nick Clegg]], [[Ed Balls]], and [[Derek Jacobi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordunimediasoc.com/orb-a-spotlight|title=Spotlight: The Oxford Review of Books (ORB)|website=www.oxfordunimediasoc.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nThe ''ORB'' holds a termly fiction competition which is judged by a prominent author or poet. Past judges have included [[Victoria Hislop]], [[Chris Power]] and Julia Armfield<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/424970128084954/|title=ORB Short Fiction Competition MT19|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>. The ''ORB'' has also hosted a number of prominent speakers, including an interview and Q and A with [[Stephen Fry]] hosted at [[Worcester College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/oxford-review-of-books-stephen-fry-in-conversation-tickets-60313903509|title=Oxford Review of Books Stephen Fry In Conversation Tickets|website=www.eventbrite.co.uk|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>, as well as a panel discussing the Irish Border featuring Andrew O'Neill, the Irish [[Ambassador]] to the [[United Kingdom]] at the time<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talks.ox.ac.uk/talks/id/ec4601b2-9eaa-4636-832b-a96cb2975a15/|title=ORB Panel Discussion on the History, Literature and Politics of the Irish Border|website=talks.ox.ac.uk|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|29em}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{notability|periodicals|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox Newspaper\n|name = Oxford Review of Books\n|type = Termly [[magazine]] during [[Oxford University]] term time\n|format = [[Broadsheet]]\n|foundation = 2017\n|owners = LM Publishing Ltd\n|website = https://www.the-orb.org\n|editor=Isabella Crispino, Alexander Haveron-Jones, Ella Johnson and Natalie Perman <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-orb.org/about|title=About|website=www.the-orb.org|language=en|accessdate=2019-04-09}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''Oxford Review of Books''''' is an independent cultural review [[broadsheet]] [[magazine]] produced by students of the [[University of Oxford]] sold commercially online, and by retailers in Oxford (such as [[Blackwell's]]) and newsagents across the [[United Kingdom]] and [[Northern Ireland]]; the magazine is often abbreviated to the '''''ORB'''''. The ''ORB'' was established in 2017 by [[University of Oxford]] students and one issue is published each term during [[University of Oxford]] term time. The ''ORB'' specialises in long-form book reviews and essays, as well as diary pieces, interviews, poetry and short fiction<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-orb.org/about|title=About|website=www.the-orb.org|language=en|accessdate=2019-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==History==\n\n''Oxford Review of Books'' was founded in 2017 and its first issue was published on the 9th June. Its founding Editors were Daniel Kodsi, Katie Mennis and Benn Sheridan<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/theorb/docs/orb_issue_1_final_cmyk|title=Oxford Review of Books Volume 1 Issue 1|website=www.issuu.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>. The ''ORB'' was modelled on the [[Times Literary Supplement]] and [[London Review of Books]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lux-mag.com/orb/|title=The Oxford Review of Books: a new student culture|website=www.lux-mag.org|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==Organisation==\n\n''Oxford Review of Books'' is published with the permission of Luxury Magazines Publishing Ltd, responsible for LUX Magazine, a luxury lifestyle magazine published by Darius Sanai, an Editor-in-Chief at Cond\u00e9 Nast, and an Oxford graduate himself<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lux-mag.com/the-team/|title=The Team|website=www.lux-mag.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>, who also publishes the ''ORB''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ebe889af-4770-4ddf-9c2a-7f097328c1d9.filesusr.com/ugd/f45b4b_64f686d1c17a492b9f283f516c4b3e09.pdf|title=Publishing and Editorial Articles of Incorporation June 2019|website=www.filesusr.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>. ''Oxford Review of Books'' staff are all current [[University of Oxford]] undergraduate or postgraduate students who run the magazine while studying for their degrees. \n\nThe ''ORB'' is organised termly by a team of three to four Editors-in-Chief overseeing the production of the issue. One or two of these Editors continue on during the following term as rolling Editor(s) to ensure continuity. Editors of the publication must be current students of the [[University of Oxford]]. Although the publication is published by Darius Sanai, it enjoys editorial independence, and the ''ORB'' team are responsible for its editorial, publishing, advertising and event operations, with full responsibility for the contents and design of the publication as well as its print and distribution, events and marketing. Current Editors are advised and supported by ''The ORB'' Advisory Board (the Board), an assembly of founders and former Editors of the ''ORB'' who provide advice and guidance to the publication<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ebe889af-4770-4ddf-9c2a-7f097328c1d9.filesusr.com/ugd/f45b4b_64f686d1c17a492b9f283f516c4b3e09.pdf|title=Publishing and Editorial Articles of Incorporation June 2019|website=www.filesusr.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.\n\nThe ''ORB'' Editors oversee the management of the publication's staff, who are recruited termly through a 'Call for Staff' conducted via the ''ORB'' social media platforms. A team of Commissioning Editors are appointed to work closely with the writers throughout the editorial process and develop articles for publication. Members for the Poetry and Fiction team are hired to respectively organise the ''ORB'' termly poetry night, and to oversee submissions and appoint a judge for the ''ORB'' termly short fiction competition. A Business Director works alongside a business team to manage the publication's business and advertising interests, and a social media and marketing team are responsible for the magazine's publicity. An Artistic Director is also appointed to organise a team of artists and illustrators who produce custom artwork for each piece in publication and online<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/860756181014095/|title=ORB Call for Staff TT20|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.  \n\nThe ''ORB'' releases calls for pitches termly via their social media platforms, and it is recommended that pitches such as books reviews are between 2,500-3,000 words, and essays between 2,000 to 2,500 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/909158342861806/|title=Pitch to the ORB TT20|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>.  \n\n==Format and style==\n\nThe ''ORB'' is unique amongst student publications in [[Oxford]] for its emphasis on long-form writing and [[journalism]]; each issue is composed of 32 pages and its reviews, interviews and journalistic articles are interspersed with poetry and creative fiction, and regularly features a comical section of satirical or amusing of classified adverts at the back. The ''ORB'' artistic team are commissioned to produce artwork and illustrations for publication alongside print pieces<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordunimediasoc.com/orb-a-spotlight|title=Spotlight: The Oxford Review of Books (ORB)|website=www.oxfordunimediasoc.com|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>. \n\n==Notable contributors==\nThe ''ORB'' is also unusual for a student publication in its printing of original works by notable poets and writers. It had published original poetry by [[Simon Armitage]], [[Lawrence Sail]] and [[Bernard O'Donoghue]]. The ''ORB'' has also interviewed notable academics and politicians, including [[Philippe Sands]], [[Anne Sebba]], [[Mary Beard]], [[Colm T\u00f3ib\u00edn]], [[Peter Singer]], [[Kwame Anthony Appiah]], [[Helen Dunmore]], [[Amia Srinivasan]], [[Quassim Cassam]], [[Nick Clegg]], [[Ed Balls]], and [[Derek Jacobi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordunimediasoc.com/orb-a-spotlight|title=Spotlight: The Oxford Review of Books (ORB)|website=www.oxfordunimediasoc.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\nThe ''ORB'' holds a termly fiction competition which is judged by a prominent author or poet. Past judges have included [[Victoria Hislop]], [[Chris Power]] and Julia Armfield<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/events/424970128084954/|title=ORB Short Fiction Competition MT19|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>. The ''ORB'' has also hosted a number of prominent speakers, including an interview and Q and A with [[Stephen Fry]] hosted at [[Worcester College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/oxford-review-of-books-stephen-fry-in-conversation-tickets-60313903509|title=Oxford Review of Books Stephen Fry In Conversation Tickets|website=www.eventbrite.co.uk|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>, as well as a panel discussing the Irish Border featuring Andrew O'Neill, the Irish [[Ambassador]] to the [[United Kingdom]] at the time<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talks.ox.ac.uk/talks/id/ec4601b2-9eaa-4636-832b-a96cb2975a15/|title=ORB Panel Discussion on the History, Literature and Politics of the Irish Border|website=talks.ox.ac.uk|language=en|accessdate=2020-04-10}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|29em}}\n", "name_user": "Helpfuleditorox", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxford_Review_of_Books"}
