016|01|01}}\n|[[2015 Tennessee Volunteers football team|2015]]\n|[[2015 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]]\n|[[Raymond James Stadium]]\n|[[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]]\n|53,202\n|{{Sortname|Butch|Jones}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|52\n! scope=\"row\" |[[2016 Music City Bowl|Music City Bowl]]\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|{{sort|W 39|W 38\u201324}}\n|{{dts|2016|12|30}}\n|[[2016 Tennessee Volunteers football team|2016]]\n|[[2016 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]]\n|[[Nissan Stadium]]\n|[[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]]\n|68,496\n|{{Sortname|Butch|Jones}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|53\n! scope=\"row\"| [[2020 Gator Bowl|Gator Bowl]]\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|{{sort|W 01|W 23\u201322}}\n|{{dts|2020|1|2}}\n|[[2019 Tennessee Volunteers football team|2019]]\n|[[2019 Indiana Hoosiers football team|Indiana]]\n|[[TIAA Bank Field]]\n|[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]\n|61,789\n|{{Sortname|Jeremy|Pruitt}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group= \"A\"/>\n\n==References==\n;General\n*{{cite web |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/2016/Bowls.pdf |title=Bowl/All-Star Game Records |author=National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) |work=2016 NCAA Division I Football Records |publisher=NCAA.org |accessdate=December 14, 2016 |format=PDF}}\n\n;Specific\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Tennessee Volunteers bowl game navbox}}\n{{Tennessee Volunteers football navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of college bowl games by team|Tennessee Volunteers]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football bowl games|*]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBowl games", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Tennessee_Volunteers_bowl_games"}
{"title_page": "Dissidents in the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests", "text_new": "The [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], commonly known in [[mainland China]] as the '''June Fourth Incident''' ({{zh|c=\u516d\u56db\u4e8b\u4ef6|p=li\u00f9s\u00ec sh\u00ecji\u00e0n}}), were student-led [[Demonstration (people)|demonstrations]] in [[Beijing]] (the capital of the [[People's Republic of China]]) in 1989. More broadly, it refers to the popular national movement inspired by the Beijing protests during that period, sometimes called the''' '89 Democracy Movement''' ({{zh|links=no|c=\u516b\u4e5d\u6c11\u8fd0|p=b\u0101ji\u01d4 m\u00edny\u00f9n}}). The protests were forcibly suppressed after [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Premier]] [[Li Peng]] declared [[martial law]]. In what became known in the West as the '''Tiananmen Square Massacre''', [[People's Liberation Army at Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|troops with assault rifles and tanks fired at the demonstrators]] trying to block the military's advance towards [[Tiananmen Square]]. The number of civilian deaths was internally estimated by the Chinese government to be near or above 10,000.<ref name=10,000>{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|title=Declassified: Chinese official said at least 10,000 civilians died in 1989 Tiananmen massacre, documents show|date=21 December 2017|last=Cheng|first=Kris|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/12/21/declassified-chinese-official-said-least-10000-civilians-died-1989-tiananmen-massacre-documents-show/|access-date=22 December 2017}} Political chief of 38th Army Li Zhiyun and US Government documents, respectively</ref><ref>Jan Wong, ''Red China Blues'', Random House 1997, p. 278.</ref>\n\nDissidents included student leaders, intellectuals and other citizens.\n\n== Student leaders ==\nOn 13 June 1989, the [[Beijing Public Security Bureau]] released an order for the arrest of 21 students who they identified as leaders of the protest.<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\">''Renmin ribao'' (People's Daily), June 14, 1989, 2.</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.standoffattiananmen.com/2012/06/document-of-1989-21-most-wanted-student.html|title=Document of 1989: 21 Most Wanted Student Leaders|last=Cheng|first=Eddie|date=June 13, 2012|website=Standoff at Tiananmen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413065416/http://www.standoffattiananmen.com/2012/06/document-of-1989-21-most-wanted-student.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> These 21 most wanted student leaders were part of the [[Beijing Students' Autonomous Federation|Beijing Students Autonomous Federation]]<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> which had been an instrumental student organization in the Tiananmen Square protests. Prominent leaders such as [[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]], [[Wu'erkaixi|Wu'er Kaixi]] and [[Chai Ling]] topped the list. Immediately after the release of the list, only 7 out of the 21 Most Wanted escaped China, with assistance from the Hong-Kong based organization [[Operation Yellowbird]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=70\u201371}}</ref> Though decades have passed, the Most Wanted list has never been retracted by the Chinese government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|page=74}}</ref>\n\n=== Official release ===\nThe Beijing Public Security Bureau issued the 21 Most Wanted list with the following description:\n{{quote|The illegal organization \"Beijing Students Autonomous Federation\" instigated and organized the counter-revolutionary rebellion in Beijing. It is now decided to pursue 21 of its head and key members, including Wang Dan. After receiving this order, please immediately arrange investigation work. If found, immediate arrest the targets and inform the Beijing Public Security Bureau.<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/>}}\n\nPhotographs with biographical descriptions of the 21 Most Wanted followed in this order on the poster:\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=2|Name !! Age or date of birth !! Origin !! Other remarks or characteristics\n|-\n|[[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]] || Male || 26 February 1969 || Jilin || Student of the Department of History at [[Peking University]], 173&nbsp;cm tall, thin hair, slim build, wears glasses, Beijing accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Wu'erkaixi|Wuer Kaixi]] || Male || 17 February 1968 || Xinjiang || Student of the Department of Education at [[Beijing Normal University]], 174&nbsp;cm tall, long face, big eyes, thick lips, often wearing green army pants<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Liu Gang]] || Male || 28 || Liaoyuan City, Jilin Province || Former graduate student of Department of Physics at Peking University, now unemployed, 165&nbsp;cm tall, square face, northeastern accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Chai Ling]] || Female || 15 April 1966 || Rizhao City, Shandong Province || Han nationality, graduate student of Department of Psychology at Beijing Normal University, 156&nbsp;cm tall, round face, high cheekbones, short hair, white skin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhou Fengsuo || Male || 5 October 1967 || Chang'an County, Shaanxi Province || Han nationality, student of Department of Physics, [[Tsinghua University]], 176&nbsp;cm tall, square face, pointed chin, heavy eyebrows<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhai Weimin || Male || 21 || Xin'an County, Henan Province || Student of Beijing Institute of Economics., 168&nbsp;cm tall, thin build, long-face, dark complexion, heavy Henan accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Liang Qingdun || Male || 11 May 1969 || Pengxi, Sichuan Province || Student of Department of Psychology at Beijing Normal University, 171&nbsp;cm tall, lean, darker complexion, rectangular face, small eyes, high nose, thick lips, speaks Mandarin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Wang Zhengyun || Male || October 1968 || Lives in Nanke District, Jinping County, Honghe Prefecture, Yunnan Province||Student of Central Institute of Nationalities ([[Minzu University of China]]), 167&nbsp;cm tall, thin and long-faced, dark-yellow eyes, small dots, Yunnan accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zheng Xuguang || Male || 20 || Native of Mi County, Henan Province || Lives in No. 56, North Lane, Huancheng West Road, Xi'an, student of [[Beijing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics]], 181&nbsp;cm tall, weighing 63 kilograms, long round face, sharp chin, big ears<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Ma Shaofang || Male || November 1964 || Jiangsu || Student of [[Beijing Film Academy]], 167&nbsp;cm tall, lean, long-faced, sharp chin, dark complexion, wears glasses<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Yang Tao || Male || 19 || Fuzhou, Fujian Province || Student of Department of History at Peking University. 170&nbsp;cm tall, thin, high cheekbones, wears glasses, speaks Mandarin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Wang Zhixing || Male || November 1967 || Shanxi || Student of the [[China University of Political Science and Law]], lives in Shanxi Yuci City Textile Industry School, 169&nbsp;cm tall, long hair, wears glasses<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Feng Congde]] || Male || 5 March 1966 || Sichuan || Graduate student of Institute of Remote Sensing at Peking University, lean, darker complexion, large nose<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/><p>\n|-\n|Wang Chaohua || Female || 37 || Unknown || Graduate student of [[Chinese Academy of Social Sciences]], 163&nbsp;cm tall, relatively thin, with a relatively flat face, triangular eyes, short hair<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p><p>\n|-\n|Wang Youcai || Male || June 1966 || Zhejiang||Graduate student of Department of Physics at Peking University<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p>\n|-\n|Zhang Zhiqing || Male || June 1964 || Taiyuan City, Shanxi Province || Student of the China University of Political Science and Law<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhang Boli || Male || 26 || Wang Kui County, Heilongjiang Province || Student of Peking University, more fat, round face, thick lips, northeastern accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/><p>\n|-\n|[[Li Lu]] || Male || 6 April 1966 || Tangshan, Hebei Province || Student of [[Nanjing University|Nanking University]], 174&nbsp;cm tall, medium build with square chin, prominent lower teeth<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p>\n|-\n|Zhang Ming || Male || April 1965 || Jilin || Student of Department of Auto Engineering at Tsinghua University<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Xiong Wei || Male || July 1966 || Yingcheng County, Hubei Province || Student of Department of Radio at Tsinghua University, lives in Beijing<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Xiong Yan (dissident)|Xiong Yan]] || Male || 1 September 1964 || Hunan || Graduate student of Department of Law at Peking University, lives in Hunan Shuangfeng County<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|}\nThe 21 most wanted student leaders faces and descriptions were broadcast on television as well and were constantly looped.<ref>{{cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|page=39}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/14/world/turmoil-in-china-moderates-appear-on-beijing-tv-easing-fears-of-wholesale-purge.html|title=TURMOIL IN CHINA; Moderates Appear on Beijing TV, Easing Fears of Wholesale Purge|last=Kristof|first=Nicholas D|date=June 14, 1989|work=New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413072522/https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/14/world/turmoil-in-china-moderates-appear-on-beijing-tv-easing-fears-of-wholesale-purge.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Arrests were also broadcast, such as that of Most Wanted No. 21 Xiong Yan.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=A Heart for Freedom|last=Chai|first=Ling|publisher=Tyndale House Publishers|year=2011|isbn=|location=|page=207}}</ref>\n\nNot all of the 21 most wanted are as well known as Chai Ling or Wang Dan. Others such Zhang Zhiqing have essentially disappeared. After his initial arrest in January 1991 and subsequent release, nothing further is known about his situation and where he lives now.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zhang Zhiqing's role and reason for being listed on the list of 21 most wanted is generally unknown; this is the case for many others on the list such Wang Chaohua. Other dissidents that are not as well known to the public include Zhou Fengsuo and Wang Zhengyun. Zhou Fengsuo was a physics student at Tsinghua University and a member of the Standing Committee of the Beijing Students Autonomous Federation during the protests.<ref name=\":2\" /> Fengsuo was turned in by his sister and arrested on June 13, 1989 in Xi'an.<ref name=\"Cheng 2009 p276\">{{Cite book|title=Standoff At Tiananmen|last=Cheng|first=Eddie|publisher=Sensys Corp|year=2009|isbn=|location=|page=276}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He was imprisoned for one year before being released in 1990 due to international pressures, along with 97 other political prisoners.<ref name=\":2\" /> Leaving China for the United States, he attended the University of Chicago.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/tiananmens-most-wanted/?mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted|last=Jacobs|first=Andrew|date=June 3, 2014|work=Sinosphere, New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415080207/https://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/tiananmens-most-wanted/?mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Steady in his activist roots he co-founded Humanitarian China, an organization that promotes rule of law in China and also raises money for Chinese political prisoners.<ref name=\":6\" /> Wang Zhengyun was a student of the [[Central University for Nationalities]] and was the only member of the [[Kucong|Kucon]] ethnicity minority group to be studying at a university.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zhengyun was arrested in July 1989 and released two years later.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was sent back to his village in the Yunnan countryside.<ref name=\":2\" /> In December 1998, Wang was one of 19 dissidents, including Zhai Weimin, who staged a hunger strike to protest the oppression of [[Democracy Party of China|CDP]] members and other dissidents.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMa Shaofang and Yang Tao are another pair of dissidents that lack public attention despite their constant activist efforts. Ma Shaofang was a student of the Beijing Film Academy during the protests and turned himself in on 13 June 1989.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\"Cheng 2009 p276\"/> In October 1990 he was sentenced to three years in prison for counterrevolutionary incitement.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted\u2014Where Are They Now?|last=Mosher|first=Stacy|date=May 26, 2004|website=HRI China|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071105/https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May 1994, he participated with Wang Dan and other dissidents in a petition to the National People's Congress calling for a reassessment of 4 June.<ref name=\":23\" /> He has had issues in attempting to open a business and has had a series of short lived jobs ever since and is living in Shenzhen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/mashaofang.htm|title=Where Are Some of the \"Most Wanted\" Participants Today?|date=May 24, 2004|website=Human Rights Watch Asia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416181118/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/mashaofang.htm|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":23\" /> Yang Tao, who was at one time the head of Beijing University's Autonomous Student Federation, remains in China today.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":04\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/yangtao.htm|title=Where Are Some of the \"Most Wanted\" Participants Today?|date=May 24, 2005|website=Human Rights Watch Asia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416181529/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/yangtao.htm|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was initially charged as being an instigator of the counterrevolutionary rebellion and imprisoned for one year on 16 June 1989.<ref name=\":23\" /> In 1998, he wrote an open letter asking for the release of Wang Youcai.<ref name=\":04\" /> His continued efforts landed him in prison in 1999 after lobbying for the government to reverse the labeling of the protest as a \"counterrevolutionary rebellion\".<ref name=\":04\" /> He was originally arrested on charges of \"incitement to overthrow state political power.\"<ref name=\":04\" /><ref name=\":23\" /> However, he was indicted on amended charges of tax evasion on 23 December due to lack of evidence and on 5 January 2003 was sentenced to four years in prison.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":04\" /> He was released in May 2003.<ref name=\":23\" /> Yang too has had trouble earning a living.<ref name=\":04\" />\n\n=== Aftermath ===\nEach of the 21 students faced diverse experiences after their arrests or escapes; while some remain abroad with no intent to return, others have chosen to stay indefinitely such as Zhang Ming.<ref name=\":7\" /> Only 7 of the 21 were able to escape, the remainder of the 21 student leaders were apprehended and incarcerated.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted\u2014Where Are They Now?|last=Mosher|first=Stacy|date=May 26, 2004|website=HRI China|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071105/https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Zhou Fengsuo was turned in by his own sister and arrested on 13 June 1989 in Xi'an. He was imprisoned for one year before being released in 1990 due to international pressures, along with 97 other political prisoners.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some served longer sentences than others, such as Wang Dan, one of the most visible leaders during the protests topping the most wanted list.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tiananmen Exiles: Voices of the Struggle for Democracy in China|last=Xiaoqing|first=Rowena|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=14\u201315}}</ref> Wang Dan continued his activist efforts after his parole release and was subsequently sentenced to 11 years for subversion.<ref name=\":2\" /> Liu Gang, who was arrested in Baoding in mid June,<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://pantheon.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/China0791.PDF|title=Guilt by Association, More Documents from the Chinese Trials|publisher=Asia Watch|date=July 25, 1991|website=www.hrw.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415074718/http://pantheon.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/China0791.PDF|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> attempted to organize his fellow prisoners in defiance, by conducting a hunger strike.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=40\u201342}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> He had his arms lashed behind his back in a harsh position for several days while in prison.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many of those who initially escaped from the most wanted list were assisted by Operation Yellowbird and fled to the West.<ref name=\":7\" /> Those who escaped remain in exile today and have opened up about their experiences. Zhang Boli, number 17 on the list wrote a book titled \"[[Escape from China|Escape From China]]\" that details his experience during the protests and his escape.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Escape From China|last=Boli|first=Zhang|publisher=Washington Square Press|year=1998|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Those who escaped, whether it was in 1989 or after, generally have had difficulty re-entering China, even up to this day.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=73\u201376}}</ref> The Chinese government prefers to leave the dissidents in exile.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/11/25/why-china-refuses-to-arrest-its-most-wanted-dissidents/|title=Why China Refuses to Arrest its 'Most Wanted' Dissidents|last=Traywick|first=Catherine A.|date=November 25, 2013|work=Foreign Policy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071609/http://foreignpolicy.com/2013/11/25/why-china-refuses-to-arrest-its-most-wanted-dissidents/|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Those who attempt to re-enter, such as Wu'er Kaixi, have been simply sent back, but not arrested.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2009, Xiong Yan, number 21 on the list, returned to China with a visit to Hong Kong, a special administrative region of China, in order to mark the 20th anniversary the Tiananmen protests.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/asiapcf/06/02/tiananmen.xiong.yan/index.html|title=One of Tiananmen's 'most wanted' returns to China|last=Leitsinger|first=Miranda|date=June 4, 2009|work=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415201249/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/asiapcf/06/02/tiananmen.xiong.yan/index.html|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Xiong Yan spent 19 months in jail, after his release he fled to the United States where he keeps in touch with Tiananmen activists and participates in pro-democracy events.<ref name=\":8\" /> Xiong was invited to the southern Chinese enclave by the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China|Hong Kong Alliance]], which has been holding annual candlelight vigils on the 4 June anniversary Tiananmen protests.<ref name=\":8\" /> Many of the 21 who are in exile have joined human rights organizations or are now engaging in private business.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Arrests and punishment ===\nThe authorities carried out mass arrests. Many workers were summarily tried and executed. In contrast, the students\u2014many of whom came from relatively affluent backgrounds and were well-connected\u2014received much lighter sentences. [[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]], the student leader who topped the most wanted list, spent seven years in prison. Many of the students and university staff implicated were permanently politically stigmatized, some never to be employed again. Some student leaders such as [[Chai Ling]] and [[Wuer Kaixi]] were able to escape to the United States, the United Kingdom, France and other Western nations under [[Operation Yellowbird]] that was organized from Hong Kong, a British territory at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-18141489|title=Article: Still on the wing; inside Operation Yellowbird, the daring plot to help dissidents escape.(special report: China)|newspaper=Newsweek|date=April 1996|last1=Liu|first1=Melinda}}</ref>\n\nSmaller protest actions continued in other cities for a few days. Some university staff and students who had witnessed the killings in Beijing organized or spurred commemorative events upon their return to school. At Shanghai's prestigious [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University|Jiaotong University]], for example, the party secretary organized a public commemoration event, with engineering students producing a large metal wreath.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nAccording to the [[Dui Hua Foundation]], citing a provincial government, 1,602 individuals were imprisoned for protest-related activities in the early 1989. {{as of|2012|May|}}, at least two remain incarcerated in Beijing and five others remain unaccounted for.<ref name=\"Duihua\">[http://duihua.org/wp/?page_id=5933 \"Less Than a Dozen June Fourth Protesters Still in Prison\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227230426/https://duihua.org/wp/?page_id=5933 |date=2019-02-27 }} ''[[Dui Hua Foundation]]'' May 31, 2012</ref> In June 2014, it was reported that Miao Deshun was believed to be the last known prisoner incarcerated for their participation in the protests; he was last heard from a decade ago.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-27659475 |last = Harron |first = Celia |title = Miao Deshun: China's last Tiananmen prisoner? |newspaper=BBC News|accessdate= 23 September 2014 |date = 2014-06-03 }}</ref> All are reported to be suffering from mental illness.<ref name=\"Duihua\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=no}}\n* [http://www.tsquare.tv/ ''The Gate of Heavenly Peace \u2013 Feature-length Documentary'' And various archival documents]\n* [http://www.rfi.fr/actuen/articles/113/article_3781.asp Secret recordings resurrect Chinese PM's criticism of Tiananmen crackdown] \u2013 Radio France Internationale\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tankman/ ''The Tank Man''], 2006 PBS documentary\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3775907.stm BBC's ''Witnessing Tiananmen: Clearing the Square'' with eyewitness accounts of Tiananmen]\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB16/documents/index.html Tiananmen Square, 1989 ''The Declassified History'']\n* [http://www.rts.ch/archives/dossiers/3478295-tiananmen-1989-la-fin-des-illusions-democratiques-en-chine.html Tiananmen Dossiers and Video Clips] (in French)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140421082204/http://89concert.alliance.org.hk/ Official site of Hong Kong \"Concert For Democracy In China\"] (in Traditional Chinese)\n* [http://after64.sbs.com.au/ SBS's \"After 6/4\" interactive with Western and CPC perspectives on events of Tiananmen Square, 1989] (in English and Simplified Chinese)\n* {{cite web|url=http://multimedia.scmp.com/tiananmen/|title=Voices from Tiananmen|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|work=South China Morning Post}}\n\n{{1989 Tiananmen protests}}\n{{Fall of Communism}}\n{{PRC conflicts}}\n{{Cold War}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiananmen Square Protests Of 1989}}\n[[Category:1989 Tiananmen Square protests| ]]\n[[Category:1989 protests]]\n[[Category:Protests in China]]\n[[Category:1989 in China]]\n[[Category:1980s in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1989]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests]]\n[[Category:History of Beijing]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of China]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1989]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Political controversies in China]]\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Protest-related deaths|1989]]\n[[Category:Student protests in China]]\n[[Category:Tiananmen Square]]\n[[Category:April 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:June 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Chinese democracy movements]]\n[[Category:Censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Deng Xiaoping]]\n[[Category:Human rights in China]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in China]]\n[[Category:Socialism in China]]\n[[Category:1989 in Asia]]\n[[Category:1980s in China]]\n[[Category:20th century in Beijing]]\n", "text_old": "The [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], commonly known in [[mainland China]] as the '''June Fourth Incident''' ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: {{lang|zh|\u516d\u56db\u4e8b\u4ef6}}, ''li\u00f9s\u00ec sh\u00ecji\u00e0n''), were student-led [[Demonstration (people)|demonstrations]] in [[Beijing]] (the capital of the [[People's Republic of China]]) in 1989. More broadly, it refers to the popular national movement inspired by the Beijing protests during that period, sometimes called the''' '89 Democracy Movement''' (Chinese: {{lang|zh|\u516b\u4e5d\u6c11\u8fd0}}, ''b\u0101ji\u01d4 m\u00edny\u00f9n''). The protests were forcibly suppressed after [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Premier]] [[Li Peng]] declared [[martial law]]. In what became known in the West as the '''Tiananmen Square Massacre''', [[People's Liberation Army at Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|troops with assault rifles and tanks fired at the demonstrators]] trying to block the military's advance towards [[Tiananmen Square]]. The number of civilian deaths was internally estimated by the Chinese government to be near or above 10,000.<ref name=10,000>{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|title=Declassified: Chinese official said at least 10,000 civilians died in 1989 Tiananmen massacre, documents show|date=21 December 2017|last=Cheng|first=Kris|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/12/21/declassified-chinese-official-said-least-10000-civilians-died-1989-tiananmen-massacre-documents-show/|access-date=22 December 2017}} Political chief of 38th Army Li Zhiyun and US Government documents, respectively</ref><ref>Jan Wong, ''Red China Blues'', Random House 1997, p. 278.</ref>\n\nDissidents included student leaders, intellectuals and other citizens.\n\n== Student leaders ==\nOn 13 June 1989, the [[Beijing Public Security Bureau]] released an order for the arrest of 21 students who they identified as leaders of the protest.<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\">''Renmin ribao'' (People's Daily), June 14, 1989, 2.</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite web|url=http://www.standoffattiananmen.com/2012/06/document-of-1989-21-most-wanted-student.html|title=Document of 1989: 21 Most Wanted Student Leaders|last=Cheng|first=Eddie|date=June 13, 2012|website=Standoff at Tiananmen|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413065416/http://www.standoffattiananmen.com/2012/06/document-of-1989-21-most-wanted-student.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> These 21 most wanted student leaders were part of the [[Beijing Students' Autonomous Federation|Beijing Students Autonomous Federation]]<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\" /><ref name=\":02\" /> which had been an instrumental student organization in the Tiananmen Square protests. Prominent leaders such as [[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]], [[Wu'erkaixi|Wu'er Kaixi]] and [[Chai Ling]] topped the list. Immediately after the release of the list, only 7 out of the 21 Most Wanted escaped China, with assistance from the Hong-Kong based organization [[Operation Yellowbird]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=70\u201371}}</ref> Though decades have passed, the Most Wanted list has never been retracted by the Chinese government.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|page=74}}</ref>\n\n=== Official release ===\nThe Beijing Public Security Bureau issued the 21 Most Wanted list with the following description:\n{{quote|The illegal organization \"Beijing Students Autonomous Federation\" instigated and organized the counter-revolutionary rebellion in Beijing. It is now decided to pursue 21 of its head and key members, including Wang Dan. After receiving this order, please immediately arrange investigation work. If found, immediate arrest the targets and inform the Beijing Public Security Bureau.<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/>}}\n\nPhotographs with biographical descriptions of the 21 Most Wanted followed in this order on the poster:\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!colspan=2|Name !! Age or date of birth !! Origin !! Other remarks or characteristics\n|-\n|[[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]] || Male || 26 February 1969 || Jilin || Student of the Department of History at [[Peking University]], 173&nbsp;cm tall, thin hair, slim build, wears glasses, Beijing accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Wu'erkaixi|Wuer Kaixi]] || Male || 17 February 1968 || Xinjiang || Student of the Department of Education at [[Beijing Normal University]], 174&nbsp;cm tall, long face, big eyes, thick lips, often wearing green army pants<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Liu Gang]] || Male || 28 || Liaoyuan City, Jilin Province || Former graduate student of Department of Physics at Peking University, now unemployed, 165&nbsp;cm tall, square face, northeastern accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Chai Ling]] || Female || 15 April 1966 || Rizhao City, Shandong Province || Han nationality, graduate student of Department of Psychology at Beijing Normal University, 156&nbsp;cm tall, round face, high cheekbones, short hair, white skin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhou Fengsuo || Male || 5 October 1967 || Chang'an County, Shaanxi Province || Han nationality, student of Department of Physics, [[Tsinghua University]], 176&nbsp;cm tall, square face, pointed chin, heavy eyebrows<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhai Weimin || Male || 21 || Xin'an County, Henan Province || Student of Beijing Institute of Economics., 168&nbsp;cm tall, thin build, long-face, dark complexion, heavy Henan accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Liang Qingdun || Male || 11 May 1969 || Pengxi, Sichuan Province || Student of Department of Psychology at Beijing Normal University, 171&nbsp;cm tall, lean, darker complexion, rectangular face, small eyes, high nose, thick lips, speaks Mandarin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Wang Zhengyun || Male || October 1968 || Lives in Nanke District, Jinping County, Honghe Prefecture, Yunnan Province||Student of Central Institute of Nationalities ([[Minzu University of China]]), 167&nbsp;cm tall, thin and long-faced, dark-yellow eyes, small dots, Yunnan accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zheng Xuguang || Male || 20 || Native of Mi County, Henan Province || Lives in No. 56, North Lane, Huancheng West Road, Xi'an, student of [[Beijing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics]], 181&nbsp;cm tall, weighing 63 kilograms, long round face, sharp chin, big ears<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Ma Shaofang || Male || November 1964 || Jiangsu || Student of [[Beijing Film Academy]], 167&nbsp;cm tall, lean, long-faced, sharp chin, dark complexion, wears glasses<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Yang Tao || Male || 19 || Fuzhou, Fujian Province || Student of Department of History at Peking University. 170&nbsp;cm tall, thin, high cheekbones, wears glasses, speaks Mandarin<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Wang Zhixing || Male || November 1967 || Shanxi || Student of the [[China University of Political Science and Law]], lives in Shanxi Yuci City Textile Industry School, 169&nbsp;cm tall, long hair, wears glasses<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Feng Congde]] || Male || 5 March 1966 || Sichuan || Graduate student of Institute of Remote Sensing at Peking University, lean, darker complexion, large nose<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/><p>\n|-\n|Wang Chaohua || Female || 37 || Unknown || Graduate student of [[Chinese Academy of Social Sciences]], 163&nbsp;cm tall, relatively thin, with a relatively flat face, triangular eyes, short hair<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p><p>\n|-\n|Wang Youcai || Male || June 1966 || Zhejiang||Graduate student of Department of Physics at Peking University<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p>\n|-\n|Zhang Zhiqing || Male || June 1964 || Taiyuan City, Shanxi Province || Student of the China University of Political Science and Law<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Zhang Boli || Male || 26 || Wang Kui County, Heilongjiang Province || Student of Peking University, more fat, round face, thick lips, northeastern accent<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/><p>\n|-\n|[[Li Lu]] || Male || 6 April 1966 || Tangshan, Hebei Province || Student of [[Nanjing University|Nanking University]], 174&nbsp;cm tall, medium build with square chin, prominent lower teeth<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/></p>\n|-\n|Zhang Ming || Male || April 1965 || Jilin || Student of Department of Auto Engineering at Tsinghua University<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|Xiong Wei || Male || July 1966 || Yingcheng County, Hubei Province || Student of Department of Radio at Tsinghua University, lives in Beijing<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|-\n|[[Xiong Yan (dissident)|Xiong Yan]] || Male || 1 September 1964 || Hunan || Graduate student of Department of Law at Peking University, lives in Hunan Shuangfeng County<ref name=\"peoplesdaily\"/><ref name=\":02\"/>\n|}\nThe 21 most wanted student leaders faces and descriptions were broadcast on television as well and were constantly looped.<ref>{{cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|page=39}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/14/world/turmoil-in-china-moderates-appear-on-beijing-tv-easing-fears-of-wholesale-purge.html|title=TURMOIL IN CHINA; Moderates Appear on Beijing TV, Easing Fears of Wholesale Purge|last=Kristof|first=Nicholas D|date=June 14, 1989|work=New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413072522/https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/14/world/turmoil-in-china-moderates-appear-on-beijing-tv-easing-fears-of-wholesale-purge.html|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Arrests were also broadcast, such as that of Most Wanted No. 21 Xiong Yan.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book|title=A Heart for Freedom|last=Chai|first=Ling|publisher=Tyndale House Publishers|year=2011|isbn=|location=|page=207}}</ref>\n\nNot all of the 21 most wanted are as well known as Chai Ling or Wang Dan. Others such Zhang Zhiqing have essentially disappeared. After his initial arrest in January 1991 and subsequent release, nothing further is known about his situation and where he lives now.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zhang Zhiqing's role and reason for being listed on the list of 21 most wanted is generally unknown; this is the case for many others on the list such Wang Chaohua. Other dissidents that are not as well known to the public include Zhou Fengsuo and Wang Zhengyun. Zhou Fengsuo was a physics student at Tsinghua University and a member of the Standing Committee of the Beijing Students Autonomous Federation during the protests.<ref name=\":2\" /> Fengsuo was turned in by his sister and arrested on June 13, 1989 in Xi'an.<ref name=\"Cheng 2009 p276\">{{Cite book|title=Standoff At Tiananmen|last=Cheng|first=Eddie|publisher=Sensys Corp|year=2009|isbn=|location=|page=276}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> He was imprisoned for one year before being released in 1990 due to international pressures, along with 97 other political prisoners.<ref name=\":2\" /> Leaving China for the United States, he attended the University of Chicago.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/tiananmens-most-wanted/?mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted|last=Jacobs|first=Andrew|date=June 3, 2014|work=Sinosphere, New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415080207/https://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/03/tiananmens-most-wanted/?mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Steady in his activist roots he co-founded Humanitarian China, an organization that promotes rule of law in China and also raises money for Chinese political prisoners.<ref name=\":6\" /> Wang Zhengyun was a student of the [[Central University for Nationalities]] and was the only member of the [[Kucong|Kucon]] ethnicity minority group to be studying at a university.<ref name=\":2\" /> Zhengyun was arrested in July 1989 and released two years later.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was sent back to his village in the Yunnan countryside.<ref name=\":2\" /> In December 1998, Wang was one of 19 dissidents, including Zhai Weimin, who staged a hunger strike to protest the oppression of [[Democracy Party of China|CDP]] members and other dissidents.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMa Shaofang and Yang Tao are another pair of dissidents that lack public attention despite their constant activist efforts. Ma Shaofang was a student of the Beijing Film Academy during the protests and turned himself in on 13 June 1989.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\"Cheng 2009 p276\"/> In October 1990 he was sentenced to three years in prison for counterrevolutionary incitement.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted\u2014Where Are They Now?|last=Mosher|first=Stacy|date=May 26, 2004|website=HRI China|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071105/https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May 1994, he participated with Wang Dan and other dissidents in a petition to the National People's Congress calling for a reassessment of 4 June.<ref name=\":23\" /> He has had issues in attempting to open a business and has had a series of short lived jobs ever since and is living in Shenzhen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/mashaofang.htm|title=Where Are Some of the \"Most Wanted\" Participants Today?|date=May 24, 2004|website=Human Rights Watch Asia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416181118/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/mashaofang.htm|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\":23\" /> Yang Tao, who was at one time the head of Beijing University's Autonomous Student Federation, remains in China today.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":04\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/yangtao.htm|title=Where Are Some of the \"Most Wanted\" Participants Today?|date=May 24, 2005|website=Human Rights Watch Asia|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416181529/https://www.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/yangtao.htm|archive-date=2018-04-16|url-status=dead}}</ref> He was initially charged as being an instigator of the counterrevolutionary rebellion and imprisoned for one year on 16 June 1989.<ref name=\":23\" /> In 1998, he wrote an open letter asking for the release of Wang Youcai.<ref name=\":04\" /> His continued efforts landed him in prison in 1999 after lobbying for the government to reverse the labeling of the protest as a \"counterrevolutionary rebellion\".<ref name=\":04\" /> He was originally arrested on charges of \"incitement to overthrow state political power.\"<ref name=\":04\" /><ref name=\":23\" /> However, he was indicted on amended charges of tax evasion on 23 December due to lack of evidence and on 5 January 2003 was sentenced to four years in prison.<ref name=\":23\" /><ref name=\":04\" /> He was released in May 2003.<ref name=\":23\" /> Yang too has had trouble earning a living.<ref name=\":04\" />\n\n=== Aftermath ===\nEach of the 21 students faced diverse experiences after their arrests or escapes; while some remain abroad with no intent to return, others have chosen to stay indefinitely such as Zhang Ming.<ref name=\":7\" /> Only 7 of the 21 were able to escape, the remainder of the 21 student leaders were apprehended and incarcerated.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|title=Tiananmen's Most Wanted\u2014Where Are They Now?|last=Mosher|first=Stacy|date=May 26, 2004|website=HRI China|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071105/https://www.hrichina.org/en/content/3747|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Zhou Fengsuo was turned in by his own sister and arrested on 13 June 1989 in Xi'an. He was imprisoned for one year before being released in 1990 due to international pressures, along with 97 other political prisoners.<ref name=\":2\" /> Some served longer sentences than others, such as Wang Dan, one of the most visible leaders during the protests topping the most wanted list.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tiananmen Exiles: Voices of the Struggle for Democracy in China|last=Xiaoqing|first=Rowena|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2014|isbn=|location=|pages=14\u201315}}</ref> Wang Dan continued his activist efforts after his parole release and was subsequently sentenced to 11 years for subversion.<ref name=\":2\" /> Liu Gang, who was arrested in Baoding in mid June,<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://pantheon.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/China0791.PDF|title=Guilt by Association, More Documents from the Chinese Trials|publisher=Asia Watch|date=July 25, 1991|website=www.hrw.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415074718/http://pantheon.hrw.org/legacy/campaigns/china/scholars/t15/China0791.PDF|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> attempted to organize his fellow prisoners in defiance, by conducting a hunger strike.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=40\u201342}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /> He had his arms lashed behind his back in a harsh position for several days while in prison.<ref name=\":5\" /> Many of those who initially escaped from the most wanted list were assisted by Operation Yellowbird and fled to the West.<ref name=\":7\" /> Those who escaped remain in exile today and have opened up about their experiences. Zhang Boli, number 17 on the list wrote a book titled \"[[Escape from China|Escape From China]]\" that details his experience during the protests and his escape.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Escape From China|last=Boli|first=Zhang|publisher=Washington Square Press|year=1998|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Those who escaped, whether it was in 1989 or after, generally have had difficulty re-entering China, even up to this day.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The People's Republic of Amnesia: Tiananmen Revisited|last=Lim|first=Louisa|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2015|isbn=|location=|pages=73\u201376}}</ref> The Chinese government prefers to leave the dissidents in exile.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/11/25/why-china-refuses-to-arrest-its-most-wanted-dissidents/|title=Why China Refuses to Arrest its 'Most Wanted' Dissidents|last=Traywick|first=Catherine A.|date=November 25, 2013|work=Foreign Policy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180413071609/http://foreignpolicy.com/2013/11/25/why-china-refuses-to-arrest-its-most-wanted-dissidents/|archive-date=2018-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Those who attempt to re-enter, such as Wu'er Kaixi, have been simply sent back, but not arrested.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 2009, Xiong Yan, number 21 on the list, returned to China with a visit to Hong Kong, a special administrative region of China, in order to mark the 20th anniversary the Tiananmen protests.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/asiapcf/06/02/tiananmen.xiong.yan/index.html|title=One of Tiananmen's 'most wanted' returns to China|last=Leitsinger|first=Miranda|date=June 4, 2009|work=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415201249/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/asiapcf/06/02/tiananmen.xiong.yan/index.html|archive-date=2018-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> Xiong Yan spent 19 months in jail, after his release he fled to the United States where he keeps in touch with Tiananmen activists and participates in pro-democracy events.<ref name=\":8\" /> Xiong was invited to the southern Chinese enclave by the [[Hong Kong Alliance in Support of Patriotic Democratic Movements in China|Hong Kong Alliance]], which has been holding annual candlelight vigils on the 4 June anniversary Tiananmen protests.<ref name=\":8\" /> Many of the 21 who are in exile have joined human rights organizations or are now engaging in private business.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Arrests and punishment ===\nThe authorities carried out mass arrests. Many workers were summarily tried and executed. In contrast, the students\u2014many of whom came from relatively affluent backgrounds and were well-connected\u2014received much lighter sentences. [[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]], the student leader who topped the most wanted list, spent seven years in prison. Many of the students and university staff implicated were permanently politically stigmatized, some never to be employed again. Some student leaders such as [[Chai Ling]] and [[Wuer Kaixi]] were able to escape to the United States, the United Kingdom, France and other Western nations under [[Operation Yellowbird]] that was organized from Hong Kong, a British territory at the time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-18141489|title=Article: Still on the wing; inside Operation Yellowbird, the daring plot to help dissidents escape.(special report: China)|newspaper=Newsweek|date=April 1996|last1=Liu|first1=Melinda}}</ref>\n\nSmaller protest actions continued in other cities for a few days. Some university staff and students who had witnessed the killings in Beijing organized or spurred commemorative events upon their return to school. At Shanghai's prestigious [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University|Jiaotong University]], for example, the party secretary organized a public commemoration event, with engineering students producing a large metal wreath.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}\n\nAccording to the [[Dui Hua Foundation]], citing a provincial government, 1,602 individuals were imprisoned for protest-related activities in the early 1989. {{as of|2012|May|}}, at least two remain incarcerated in Beijing and five others remain unaccounted for.<ref name=\"Duihua\">[http://duihua.org/wp/?page_id=5933 \"Less Than a Dozen June Fourth Protesters Still in Prison\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227230426/https://duihua.org/wp/?page_id=5933 |date=2019-02-27 }} ''[[Dui Hua Foundation]]'' May 31, 2012</ref> In June 2014, it was reported that Miao Deshun was believed to be the last known prisoner incarcerated for their participation in the protests; he was last heard from a decade ago.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://m.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-27659475 |last = Harron |first = Celia |title = Miao Deshun: China's last Tiananmen prisoner? |newspaper=BBC News|accessdate= 23 September 2014 |date = 2014-06-03 }}</ref> All are reported to be suffering from mental illness.<ref name=\"Duihua\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links|voy=no}}\n* [http://www.tsquare.tv/ ''The Gate of Heavenly Peace \u2013 Feature-length Documentary'' And various archival documents]\n* [http://www.rfi.fr/actuen/articles/113/article_3781.asp Secret recordings resurrect Chinese PM's criticism of Tiananmen crackdown] \u2013 Radio France Internationale\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tankman/ ''The Tank Man''], 2006 PBS documentary\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/3775907.stm BBC's ''Witnessing Tiananmen: Clearing the Square'' with eyewitness accounts of Tiananmen]\n* [http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB16/documents/index.html Tiananmen Square, 1989 ''The Declassified History'']\n* [http://www.rts.ch/archives/dossiers/3478295-tiananmen-1989-la-fin-des-illusions-democratiques-en-chine.html Tiananmen Dossiers and Video Clips] (in French)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140421082204/http://89concert.alliance.org.hk/ Official site of Hong Kong \"Concert For Democracy In China\"] (in Traditional Chinese)\n* [http://after64.sbs.com.au/ SBS's \"After 6/4\" interactive with Western and CPC perspectives on events of Tiananmen Square, 1989] (in English and Simplified Chinese)\n* {{cite web|url=http://multimedia.scmp.com/tiananmen/|title=Voices from Tiananmen|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|work=South China Morning Post}}\n\n{{1989 Tiananmen protests}}\n{{Fall of Communism}}\n{{PRC conflicts}}\n{{Cold War}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tiananmen Square Protests Of 1989}}\n[[Category:1989 Tiananmen Square protests| ]]\n[[Category:1989 protests]]\n[[Category:Protests in China]]\n[[Category:1989 in China]]\n[[Category:1980s in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1989]]\n[[Category:Civil rights protests]]\n[[Category:History of Beijing]]\n[[Category:Cold War history of China]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 1989]]\n[[Category:Massacres in China]]\n[[Category:Political controversies in China]]\n[[Category:Political repression in China]]\n[[Category:Protest-related deaths|1989]]\n[[Category:Student protests in China]]\n[[Category:Tiananmen Square]]\n[[Category:April 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:May 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:June 1989 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Chinese democracy movements]]\n[[Category:Censorship in China]]\n[[Category:Deng Xiaoping]]\n[[Category:Human rights in China]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in China]]\n[[Category:Socialism in China]]\n[[Category:1989 in Asia]]\n[[Category:1980s in China]]\n[[Category:20th century in Beijing]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:=> Chinese language templates, replaced: (Chinese: \u2192 ({{zh|links=no|c=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dissidents_in_the_1989_Tiananmen_Square_protests"}
{"title_page": "2017 Boise State Broncos football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n|mode=football\n|year=2017\n|team=Boise State Broncos\n|image=Boise State \"B\" logo.svg\n|logo_size=150\n|conference=Mountain West Conference\n|division=Mountain Division\n|short_conf=MW\n|CoachRank=22\n|APRank=22\n|CFPRank=\n|record=11\u20133\n|conf_record=7\u20131\n|head_coach=[[Bryan Harsin]]\n|hc_year=4th\n|off_coach=Zak Hill\n|oc_year=2nd\n|off_scheme=[[Multiple offense|Multiple]]\n|def_coach=Andy Avalos\n|dc_year=2nd\n|def_scheme=Multiple\n|stadium=[[Albertsons Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 36,387)\n|champion=Mountain West champion<br>MW Mountain Division champion<br />Las Vegas Bowl champion\n|conf_champ=[[2017 Mountain West Conference Football Championship Game|MW Championship Game]]\n|conf_champ_result=W 17\u201314 vs. [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]]\n|bowl= [[2017 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]]\n|bowl_result= W 38\u201328 vs. [[2017 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]]\n}}\n{{2017 Mountain West Conference football standings}}\nThe '''2017 Boise State Broncos football team''' represented [[Boise State University]] during the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. This season was the Broncos' 81st season overall, seventh as a member of the [[Mountain West Conference]] and fifth within the Mountain Division. The Broncos played their home games at [[Albertsons Stadium]] in [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], [[Idaho]]. They were led by fourth-year head coach [[Bryan Harsin]]. They finished the season 11\u20133, 7\u20131 in Mountain West play to win the Mountain Division. They defeated West Division champion [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]] in the [[2017 Mountain West Conference Football Championship Game|Mountain West Championship Game]] to become Mountain West champions. They were invited to the [[2017 Las Vegas Bowl|Las Vegas Bowl]] where they defeated [[2017 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]].\n\n==Preseason==\n===Award watch lists===\nListed in the order that they were released.\n\n'''[[Rimington Trophy]]''' \u2013 Sr. C Mason Hampton<ref>{{cite web|title=Rimington Trophy Press Release|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2016-17/misc_non_event/2017RimingtonSpringList.pdf|date=May 22, 2017|accessdate=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Chuck Bednarik Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Bednarik Award Watch List|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_Bednarik_Award_Watch_List.pdf|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Maxwell Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB [[Brett Rypien]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 Maxwell Award Watch List|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_Maxwell_Award_Watch_List.pdf|date=July 10, 2017|accessdate=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]]''' \u2013 Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Bronko Nagurski Trophy watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-13/college-football-2017-bronko-nagurski-trophy-watch-list|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Outland Trophy]]''' \u2013 Sr. OT Archie Lewis & Jr. DT David Moa<ref>{{cite web|title=2017 OUTLAND TROPHY WATCH LIST UNVEILED|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/bosu/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/2017-18/misc_non_event/2017_outland_trophy_preseason.pdf|date=July 13, 2017|accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[John Mackey Award]]''' \u2013 Sr. TE Jake Roh<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 John Mackey Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-11/college-football-2017-john-mackey-award-watch-list|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Paul Hornung Award]]''' \u2013 Sr. WR Cedrick Wilson<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Paul Hornung Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-17/college-football-2017-paul-hornung-award-watch-list|date=July 17, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Fred Biletnikoff Award]]''' \u2013 Sr. WR Cedrick Wilson<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Biletnikoff Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-18/college-football-2017-biletnikoff-award-watch-list|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Wuerffel Trophy]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB Brett Rypien<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Danny Wuerffel Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-18/college-football-2017-danny-wuerffel-award-watch-list|date=July 18, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Davey O'Brien Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB Brett Rypien<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Davey O'Brien Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-19/college-football-2017-davey-obrien-award-watch-list|date=July 19, 2017|accessdate=July 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Walter Camp Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB Brett Rypien<ref>{{cite web|title=College football: 2017 Walter Camp Award watch list|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/football/article/2017-07-21/college-football-2017-walter-camp-award-watch-list|date=July 21, 2017|accessdate=July 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n'''[[Manning Award]]''' \u2013 Jr. QB Brett Rypien<ref>{{cite web|title=Manning Award Watch List, 2017-18|url=https://www.allstatesugarbowl.org/site980.php|accessdate=August 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Mountain West media days===\nAt the Mountain West media days, held at the [[Cosmopolitan of Las Vegas|Cosmopolitan]] in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]], the Broncos were picked as the overwhelming favorites to win the Mountain Division title, receiving 21 of a possible 28 first place votes.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tust|first1=Jay|title=Boise State and San Diego State picked to meet in 2017 MW Championship Game|url=http://www.ktvb.com/sports/ncaaf/boise-state/boise-state-and-san-diego-state-picked-to-meet-in-2017-mw-championship-game/459373224|website=KTVB.com|publisher=TEGNA|date=July 25, 2017|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref> Sr. OL Mason Hampton was selected to the all-conference first team offense. Jr. DL David Moa and Jr. DB Tyler Horton were selected to the all-conference first team defense.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gagliardi|first1=Robert|title=UW's Allen, Wingard named preseason MW players of the year|url=http://www.wyosports.net/university_of_wyoming/football/uw-s-allen-wingard-named-preseason-mw-players-of-the/article_70219352-7142-11e7-ba68-2fb8eec27695.html|website=WyoSports.net|date=July 25, 2017|accessdate=July 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Media poll===\n====Mountain Division====\n# Boise State \u2013 161 (21)\n# Colorado State \u2013 135 (6)\n# Wyoming \u2013 114 (1)\n# Air Force \u2013 82\n# New Mexico \u2013 68\n# Utah State \u2013 28\n\n==Schedule==\n{{CFB schedule\n| rankyear = 2017\n| poll = [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football rankings#AP Poll|AP Poll]] released prior to game\n| timezone = Mountain\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 2\n| time = 1:45 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| nonconf = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[2017 Troy Trojans football team|Troy]]\n| site_stadium = [[Albertsons Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Boise, Idaho|Boise, ID]]\n| tv = [[ESPNU College Football|ESPNU]]\n| score = 24\u201313\n| attend = 31,581\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = September 9\n| time = 8:30 p.m.\n| w/l = l\n| nonconf = y\n| away = y\n| rank = \n| opponent = [[2017 Washington State Cougars football team|Washington State]]\n| opprank = 20\n| site_stadium = [[Martin Stadium]]\n| site_cityst = [[Pullman, Washington|Pullman, WA]]\n| tv = [[ESPN College Football Saturday Primetime|ESPN]]\n| score = 44\u201347\n| overtime = 3OT\n| attend = 32,631\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = {{Tooltip|September 14|Thursday}}\n| time = 6:00 p.m.\n| w/l = w\n| rank = \